 </a>
 <h2>
  <span class="mw-headline">
   The Disease
  </span>
 </h2>
 <p>
  <i>
   Campylobacter jejuni
  </i>
  is from the delta-epsilon group of proteobacteria, is a microaerophilic, Gram-negative, flagellate, spiral bacterium&#8212;properties it shares with the related gastric pathogen
  <i>
   Helicobacter pylori
  </i>
  . It is the leading cause of bacterial food-borne diarrhoeal disease throughout the world. In addition, infection with
  <i>
   C. jejuni
  </i>
  is the most frequent antecedent to a form of neuromuscular paralysis known as Guillain&#8211;Barr&#233; syndrome.
 </p>
 <a name="The_Genome">
 </a>
 <h2>
  <span class="mw-headline">
   The Genome
  </span>
 </h2>
 <p>
  The
  <i>
   C. jejuni
  </i>
  strain NCTC11168 is composed of a single circular chromosome of 1,641,481 bp , and was sequenced in collaboration with Prof. Brendan Wren of the
  <a href="http://www.lshtm.ac.uk/" class="external text" title="http://www.lshtm.ac.uk/" rel="nofollow">
   London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine
  </a>
  and Dr. Julian Ketley of the
  <a href="http://www.le.ac.uk/genetics/" class="external text" title="http://www.le.ac.uk/genetics/" rel="nofollow">
   Department of Genetics
  </a>
  , University of Leicester.
 </p>
 <a name="Data_Release">
 </a>
 <h2>
  <span class="mw-headline">
   Data Release
  </span>
 </h2>
 <p>
  A manuscript describing the genome has been published:
  <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10688204" class="external text" title="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10688204" rel="nofollow">
   Parkhill
   <i>
    et al.
   </i>
   The genome sequence of the food-borne pathogen
   <i>
    Campylobacter jejuni
   </i>
   reveals hypervariable sequences.
   <i>
    Nature
   </i>
   403:665-8
  </a>
  .  In August 2006, Ozan Gundogdu from
  <a href="http://www.lshtm.ac.uk/" class="external text" title="http://www.lshtm.ac.uk/" rel="nofollow">
   London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine
  </a>
  in collaboration with the Sanger Institute, carried out a complete
  <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17565669" class="external text" title="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17565669" rel="nofollow">
   re-annotation of the NCTC11168 genome
  </a>
  . The re-annotation has added new information to over 1450 of the original 1654 coding sequences with over 300 product functions being updated.
 </p>
